The paper deals with algorithmic and game-theoretic aspects of the matroid secretary problem, which is a classic problem in discrete optimization and has connections to various areas of computer science. The paper presents both positive and negative results for different variants of the problem, which suggests that it could be relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. Specifically, the paper involves designing algorithms, analyzing their competitive ratios, and proving lower bounds, which are typical topics in the sub-categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Moreover, the paper deals with the problem of approximating an unknown matroid, which is a common theme in the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also involves analyzing the probability of choosing the best candidate in the classical secretary problem, which could be relevant to the sub-categories of cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
